{"id": "19347", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=19347", "title": "March 28", "text": "March 28\n\nBULLET::::- AD 37 – Roman emperor Caligula accepts the titles of the Principate, bestowed on him by the Senate.\nBULLET::::- 193 – After assassinating the Roman Emperor Pertinax, his Praetorian Guards auction off the throne to Didius Julianus.\nBULLET::::- 364 – Roman Emperor Valentinian I appoints his brother Flavius Valens co-emperor.\nBULLET::::- 1566 – The foundation stone of Valletta, Malta's capital city, is laid by Jean Parisot de Valette, Grand Master of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta.\nBULLET::::- 1737 – The Marathas under Baji Rao I attack and defeat the Mughals in the Battle of Delhi.\nBULLET::::- 1776 – Juan Bautista de Anza finds the site for the Presidio of San Francisco.\nBULLET::::- 1794 – Allies under Prince Josias of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld defeat French forces at Le Cateau.\nBULLET::::- 1795 – Partitions of Poland: The Duchy of Courland and Semigallia, a northern fief of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, ceases to exist and becomes part of Imperial Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1801 – Treaty of Florence is signed, ending the war between the French Republic and the Kingdom of Naples.\nBULLET::::- 1802 – Heinrich Wilhelm Matthäus Olbers discovers 2 Pallas, the second asteroid ever to be discovered.\nBULLET::::- 1809 – Peninsular War: France defeats Spain in the Battle of Medellín.\nBULLET::::- 1814 – War of 1812: In the Battle of Valparaíso, two American naval vessels are captured by two Royal Navy vessels of equal strength.\nBULLET::::- 1842 – First concert of the Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Otto Nicolai.\nBULLET::::- 1854 – Crimean War: France and Britain declare war on Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1860 – First Taranaki War: The Battle of Waireka begins.\nBULLET::::- 1862 – American Civil War: In the Battle of Glorieta Pass, Union forces stop the Confederate invasion of the New Mexico Territory. The battle began on March 26.\nBULLET::::- 1871 – The Paris Commune is formally established in Paris.\nBULLET::::- 1883 – Tonkin Campaign: French victory in the Battle of Gia Cuc.\nBULLET::::- 1910 – Henri Fabre becomes the first person to fly a seaplane, the Fabre Hydravion, after taking off from a water runway near Martigues, France.\nBULLET::::- 1920 – Palm Sunday tornado outbreak of 1920 affects the Great Lakes region and Deep South states.\nBULLET::::- 1933 – The Imperial Airways biplane \"City of Liverpool\" is believed to be the first airliner lost to sabotage when a passenger sets a fire on board.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – Spanish Civil War: Generalissimo Francisco Franco conquers Madrid after a three-year siege.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: Britain's Mediterranean Fleet sinks three heavy cruisers and two destroyers of Italy's \"Regia Marina\".\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: A British combined force permanently disables the Louis Joubert Lock in Saint-Nazaire in order to keep the German battleship \"Tirpitz\" away from the mid-ocean convoy lanes.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – Cold War: The United States Department of State releases the Acheson–Lilienthal Report, outlining a plan for the international control of nuclear power.\nBULLET::::- 1951 – First Indochina War: In the Battle of Mạo Khê, French Union forces, led by World War II hero Jean de Lattre de Tassigny, inflict a defeat on Việt Minh forces commanded by General Võ Nguyên Giáp.\nBULLET::::- 1959 – The State Council of the People's Republic of China .\nBULLET::::- 1968 – Brazilian high school student Edson Luís de Lima Souto is killed by military police at a protest for cheaper meals at a restaurant for low-income students.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – Greek poet and Nobel Prize laureate Giorgos Seferis makes a famous statement on the BBC World Service opposing the junta in Greece.\nBULLET::::- 1970 – An earthquake strikes western Turkey at about 23:05 local time, killing 1,086 and injuring 1,260.\nBULLET::::- 1978 – The US Supreme Court hands down 5–3 decision in \"Stump v. Sparkman\", a controversial case involving involuntary sterilization and judicial immunity.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – A coolant leak at the Three Mile Island's Unit 2 nuclear reactor outside Harrisburg, Pennsylvania leads to the core overheating and a partial meltdown.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – The British House of Commons passes a vote of no confidence against James Callaghan's government by 1 vote, precipitating a general election.\nBULLET::::- 1990 – United States President George H. W. Bush posthumously awards Jesse Owens the Congressional Gold Medal.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – In South Africa, African National Congress security guards kill dozens of Inkatha Freedom Party protesters.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – Kosovo War: Serb paramilitary and military forces kill 146 Kosovo Albanians in Izbica.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – In a friendly fire incident, two American A-10 Thunderbolt II aircraft attack British tanks participating in the 2003 invasion of Iraq, killing one soldier.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – An earthquake shakes northern Sumatra with a maximum Mercalli intensity of VI (\"Strong\"), leaving 915–1,314 people dead and 340–1,146 injured.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – Massive protests are mounted against France's First Employment Contract law, meant to reduce youth unemployment.\n\nBULLET::::- 931 – Liu Chengyou, emperor of Later Han (d. 951)\nBULLET::::- 1097 – Atsiz, Abbasid caliph (d. 1156)\nBULLET::::- 1416 – Jodha of Mandore, Ruler of Marwar (d. 1489)\nBULLET::::- 1468 – Charles I, Duke of Savoy (d. 1490)\nBULLET::::- 1472 – Fra Bartolomeo, Italian painter (d. 1517)\nBULLET::::- 1483 – Raphael, Italian painter and architect (d. 1520)\nBULLET::::- 1515 – Teresa of Ávila, Spanish nun and saint (d. 1582)\nBULLET::::- 1522 – Albert the Warlike, German prince (d. 1557)\nBULLET::::- 1527 – Isabella Markham, English courtier (d. 1579)\nBULLET::::- 1591 – William Cecil, 2nd Earl of Salisbury, English earl (d. 1668)\nBULLET::::- 1592 – John Amos Comenius, Czech bishop and educator (d. 167