{"id": "19349", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=19349", "title": "May 2", "text": "May 2\n\nBULLET::::- 1194 – King Richard I of England gives Portsmouth its first Royal Charter.\nBULLET::::- 1230 – William de Braose is hanged by Prince Llywelyn the Great.\nBULLET::::- 1335 – Otto the Merry, Duke of Austria, becomes Duke of Carinthia.\nBULLET::::- 1536 – Anne Boleyn, Queen of England, is arrested and imprisoned on charges of adultery, incest, treason and witchcraft.\nBULLET::::- 1559 – John Knox returns from exile to Scotland to become the leader of the nascent Scottish Reformation.\nBULLET::::- 1568 – Mary, Queen of Scots, escapes from Loch Leven Castle.\nBULLET::::- 1611 – The King James Version of the Bible is published for the first time in London, England, by printer Robert Barker.\nBULLET::::- 1670 – King Charles II of England grants a permanent charter to the Hudson's Bay Company to open up the fur trade in North America.\nBULLET::::- 1672 – John Maitland becomes Duke of Lauderdale and Earl of March.\nBULLET::::- 1808 – Outbreak of the Peninsular War: The people of Madrid rise up in rebellion against French occupation. Francisco de Goya later memorializes this event in his painting \"The Second of May 1808\".\nBULLET::::- 1812 – The Siege of Cuautla during the Mexican War of Independence ends with both sides claiming victory after Mexican rebels under José María Morelos y Pavón abandon the city after 72 days under siege by royalist Spanish troops under Félix María Calleja.\nBULLET::::- 1816 – Marriage of Léopold of Saxe-Coburg and Princess Charlotte of Wales.\nBULLET::::- 1829 – After anchoring nearby, Captain Charles Fremantle of , declares the Swan River Colony in Australia.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: Stonewall Jackson is wounded by friendly fire while returning to camp after reconnoitering during the Battle of Chancellorsville. He succumbs to pneumonia eight days later.\nBULLET::::- 1866 – Peruvian defenders fight off the Spanish fleet at the Battle of Callao.\nBULLET::::- 1876 – The April Uprising breaks out in Ottoman Bulgaria.\nBULLET::::- 1879 – The Spanish Socialist Workers' Party is founded in Madrid by Pablo Iglesias.\nBULLET::::- 1885 – Cree and Assiniboine warriors win the Battle of Cut Knife, their largest victory over Canadian forces during the North-West Rebellion.\nBULLET::::- 1889 – Menelik II, Emperor of Ethiopia, signs the Treaty of Wuchale, giving Italy control over Eritrea.\nBULLET::::- 1906 – Closing ceremony of the Intercalated Games in Athens, Greece.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – General Motors acquires the Chevrolet Motor Company of Delaware.\nBULLET::::- 1920 – The first game of the Negro National League baseball is played in Indianapolis.\nBULLET::::- 1933 – Germany's independent labor unions are replaced by the German Labour Front.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – Following the \"coup d'état\" against Iraq Crown Prince 'Abd al-Ilah earlier that year, the United Kingdom launches the Anglo-Iraqi War to restore him to power.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: The Soviet Union announces the fall of Berlin.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: The surrender of Caserta comes into effect, by which German troops in Italy cease fighting.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: The US 82nd Airborne Division liberates Wöbbelin concentration camp finding 1000 dead prisoners, most of whom starved to death.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: A death march from Dachau to the Austrian border is halted by the segregated, all-Nisei 522nd Field Artillery Battalion of the U.S. Army in southern Bavaria, saving several hundred prisoners.\nBULLET::::- 1952 – The world's first ever jet airliner, the De Havilland Comet 1 makes its maiden flight, from London to Johannesburg.\nBULLET::::- 1955 – Tennessee Williams wins the Pulitzer Prize for Drama for \"Cat on a Hot Tin Roof\".\nBULLET::::- 1963 – Berthold Seliger launches a rocket with three stages and a maximum flight altitude of more than 100 kilometres near Cuxhaven. It is the only sounding rocket developed in Germany.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – Vietnam War: An explosion sinks the American aircraft carrier USS \"Card\" while it is docked at Saigon. Two Viet Cong combat swimmers had placed explosives on the ship's hull. She is raised and returned to service less than seven months later.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – First ascent of Shishapangma, the fourteenth highest mountain in the world and the lowest of the Eight-thousanders.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – The British ocean liner \"Queen Elizabeth 2\" departs on her maiden voyage to New York City.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – In the early morning hours a fire breaks out at the Sunshine Mine located between Kellogg and Wallace, Idaho, killing 91 workers.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – Falklands War: The British nuclear submarine sinks the Argentine cruiser ARA \"General Belgrano\".\nBULLET::::- 1986 – Chernobyl disaster: The City of Chernobyl is evacuated six days after the disaster.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – Cold War: Hungary begins dismantling its border fence with Austria, which allows a number of East Germans to defect.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – A bus crashes in Gdańsk, Poland killing 32 people.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – During the Croatian War of Independence, the Army of the Republic of Serb Krajina fires cluster bombs at Zagreb, killing seven and wounding over 175 civilians.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – The European Central Bank is founded in Brussels in order to define and execute the European Union's monetary policy.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – Panamanian general election, 1999: Mireya Moscoso becomes the first woman to be elected President of Panama.\nBULLET::::- 2000 – President Bill Clinton announces that accurate GPS access would no longer be restricted to the United States military.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The Yelwa massacre concludes. It began on 4 February 2004 when armed Muslims killed 78 Christians at Yelwa. In response, about 630 Muslims were killed by Christians on May 2nd.\nBULLET::::- 2008 – Cyclone Nargis makes landfall in Burma killing over 138,000 people and leaving millions of people homeless.\nBULLET::::- 2008 – Chaitén Volcano begins erupting in Chile, forcing the evacuation of more than 4,500 people.\nBULLET::::- 2011 – Osama bin Laden, the suspected mastermind behind the September 11 attacks and the FBI's most wanted man, is killed by the United States special forces in Abbottabad, Pakistan.\nBULLET::::- 2011 – An strikes Europe, mostly in Germany, leaving more than 30 people dead and many others sick from the bacteria outbreak.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – A pastel version of \"The Scream\", by Norwegian painter Edvard Munch, sells for $120 million in a New York City auction, setting a new world record for a work of art at auction.\nBULLET::::- 2014 – Two mudslides in Badakhshan, Afghanistan, leave up to 2,500 people missing.\nBULLET::::- 2018 – Basque separatist terrorist band ETA announces its dissolution and ceasing of all activities.\n\nBULLET::::- 1360 – Yongle Emperor of China (d. 1424)\nBULLET::::- 1402 – Eleanor of Aragon, Queen of Portugal (d. 1445)\nBULLET::::- 1451 – René II, Duke of Lorraine (d. 1508)\nBULLET::::- 1458 – Eleanor of Viseu (d. 1525)\nBULLET::::- 1476 – Charles I, Duke of Münsterberg-Oels, Count of Kladsko, Governor of Bohemia and Silesia (d. 1536)\nBULLET::::- 1533 – Philip II, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen (d. 1596)\nBULLET::::- 1551 – William Camden, English historian and topographer (d. 1623)\nBULLET::::- 1567 – Sebald de Weert, Dutch captain, vice-admiral of the Dutch East India Company (d. 1603)\nBULLET::::- 1579 – Tokugawa Hidetada, Japanese shōgun (d. 1632)\nBULLET::::- 1601 – Athanasius Kircher, German priest and scholar (d. 1680)\nBULLET::::- 1660 – Alessandro Scarlatti, Italian composer (d. 1725)\nBULLET::::- 1695 – Giovanni Niccolò Servandoni, Italian-French painter and architect (d. 1766)\nBULLET::::- 1702 – Friedrich Christoph Oetinger, German theologian and theosopher (d. 1782)\nBULLET::::- 1707 – Jean-Baptiste Barrière, French cellist and composer (d. 1747)\nBULLET