x)\nBULLET::::- Anniversary of the Dos de Mayo Uprising (Community of Madrid, Spain)\nBULLET::::- Birth Anniversary of Third Druk Gyalpo (Bhutan)\nBULLET::::- Flag Day (Poland)\nBULLET::::- Indonesia National Education Day\nBULLET::::- Teachers' Day (Iran) (Note that this date is non-Gregorian and may change according to the March Equinox, see List of observances set by the Solar Hijri calendar)\n\nBULLET::::- BBC: On This Day\nBULLET::::- Today in Canadian History\n"}
{"id": "19350", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=19350", "title": "May 3", "text": "May 3\n\nBULLET::::- 752 – Mayan king Bird Jaguar IV of Yaxchilan in modern-day Chiapas, Mexico assumes the throne.\nBULLET::::- 1294 – John II becomes Duke of Brabant, Lothier and Limburg.\nBULLET::::- 1481 – The largest of three earthquakes strikes the island of Rhodes and causes an estimated 30,000 casualties.\nBULLET::::- 1491 – Kongo monarch Nkuwu Nzinga is baptised by Portuguese missionaries, adopting the baptismal name of João I.\nBULLET::::- 1616 – Treaty of Loudun ends French civil war.\nBULLET::::- 1715 – A total solar eclipse was visible across northern Europe, and northern Asia, as predicted by Edmond Halley to within 4 minutes accuracy.\nBULLET::::- 1791 – The Constitution of May 3 (the first modern constitution in Europe) is proclaimed by the Sejm of Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth.\nBULLET::::- 1802 – Washington, D.C. is incorporated as a city after Congress abolishes the Board of Commissioners, the District's founding government. The \"City of Washington\" is given a mayor-council form of government.\nBULLET::::- 1808 – Finnish War: Sweden loses the fortress of Sveaborg to Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1808 – Peninsular War: The Madrid rebels who rose up on May 2 are executed near Príncipe Pío hill.\nBULLET::::- 1815 – Neapolitan War: Joachim Murat, King of Naples is defeated by the Austrians at the Battle of Tolentino, the decisive engagement of the war.\nBULLET::::- 1830 – The Canterbury and Whitstable Railway is opened; it is the first steam-hauled passenger railway to issue season tickets and include a tunnel.\nBULLET::::- 1837 – The University of Athens is founded in Athens, Greece.\nBULLET::::- 1848 – The boar-crested Anglo-Saxon Benty Grange helmet is discovered in a barrow on the Benty Grange farm in Derbyshire.\nBULLET::::- 1849 – The May Uprising in Dresden begins: The last of the German revolutions of 1848–49.\nBULLET::::- 1855 – American adventurer William Walker departs from San Francisco with about 60 men to conquer Nicaragua.\nBULLET::::- 1860 – Charles XV of Sweden–Norway is crowned king of Sweden.\nBULLET::::- 1867 – The Hudson's Bay Company gives up all claims to Vancouver Island.\nBULLET::::- 1901 – The Great Fire of 1901 begins in Jacksonville, Florida.\nBULLET::::- 1913 – \"Raja Harishchandra\" the first full-length Indian feature film is released, marking the beginning of the Indian film industry.\nBULLET::::- 1920 – A Bolshevik coup fails in the Democratic Republic of Georgia.\nBULLET::::- 1921 – West Virginia becomes the first state to legislate a broad sales tax, but does not implement it until a number of years later due to enforcement issues.\nBULLET::::- 1921 – The Government of Ireland Act 1920 is passed, dividing Ireland into Northern Ireland and Southern Ireland.\nBULLET::::- 1928 – The Jinan incident begins with the deaths of twelve Japanese civilians by Chinese forces in Jinan, China, which leads to Japanese retaliation and the deaths of over 2,000 Chinese civilians in the following days.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – The All India Forward Bloc is formed by Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: Japanese naval troops invade Tulagi Island in the Solomon Islands during the first part of Operation Mo that results in the Battle of the Coral Sea between Japanese forces and forces from the United States and Australia.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II; Hamburg capitulates to the British under threat of renewed bombing.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: Sinking of the prison ships \"Cap Arcona\", \"Thielbek\" and \"Deutschland\" by the Royal Air Force in Lübeck Bay.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: German Admiral-General Hans Georg von Friedeburg sent by Nazi Germany to negotiate an armistice with British Field Marshal Bernard Montgomery to end hostilities between Allies and Nazi Germany in north-west Germany.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – New post-war Japanese constitution goes into effect.\nBULLET::::- 1948 – The U.S. Supreme Court rules in \"Shelley v. Kraemer\" that covenants prohibiting the sale of real estate to blacks and other minorities are legally unenforceable.\nBULLET::::- 1951 – London's Royal Festival Hall opens with the Festival of Britain.\nBULLET::::- 1951 – The United States Senate Committee on Armed Services and United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations begin their closed door hearings into the dismissal of General Douglas MacArthur by U.S. President Harry Truman.\nBULLET::::- 1952 – Lieutenant Colonels Joseph O. Fletcher and William P. Benedict of the United States land a plane at the North Pole.\nBULLET::::- 1952 – The Kentucky Derby is televised nationally for the first time, on the CBS network.\nBULLET::::- 1957 – Walter O'Malley, the owner of the Brooklyn Dodgers, agrees to move the team from Brooklyn to Los Angeles.\nBULLET::::- 1960 – The Off-Broadway musical comedy \"The Fantasticks\" opens in New York City's Greenwich Village, eventually becoming the longest-running musical of all time.\nBULLET::::- 1960 – The Anne Frank House museum opens in Amsterdam, Netherlands.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – The police force in Birmingham, Alabama switches tactics and responds with violent force to stop the \"Birmingham campaign\" protesters. Images of the violent suppression are transmitted worldwide, bringing new-found attention to the civil rights movement.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Erich Honecker becomes First Secretary of the Socialist Unity Party of Germany, remaining in power until 1989.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – The 108-story Sears Tower in Chicago is topped out at 1,451 feet as the world's tallest building.\nBULLET::::- 1978 – The first unsolicited bulk commercial email (which would later become known as \"spam\") is sent by a Digital Equipment Corporation marketing representative to every ARPANET address on the west coast of the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1986 – Twenty-one people are killed and forty-one are injured after a bomb explodes on Air Lanka Flight 512 at Colombo airport in Sri Lanka.\nBULLET::::- 1987 – A crash by Bobby Allison at the Talladega Superspeedway, Alabama fencing at the start-finish line would lead NASCAR to develop the restrictor plate for the following season both at Daytona International Speedway and Talladega.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – The southwestern portion of Oklahoma City is devastated by an F5 tornado, killing forty-five people, injuring 665, and causing $1 billion in damage. The tornado is one of 66 from the 1999 Oklahoma tornado outbreak. This tornado also produces the highest wind speed ever recorded, measured at 301 +/- 20 mph (484 +/- 32 km/h).\nBULLET::::- 2000 – The sport of geocaching begins, with the first cache placed and the coordinates from a GPS posted on Usenet.\nBULLET::::- 2001 – The United States loses its seat on the U.N. Human Rights Commission for the first time since the commission was formed in 1947.\nBULLET::::- 2002 – An Indian Air Force MiG-21 crashes into a bank in Jalandhar, killing eight and injuring 17.\nBULLET::::- 2007 – The 3-year-old British girl Madeleine McCann disappears in Praia da Luz, Portugal, starting \"the most heavily reported missing-person case in modern history\".\nBULLET::::- 2015 – Two gunmen launch an attempted attack on an anti-Islam event in Garland, Texas, which was held in response to the \"Charlie Hebdo\" shooting.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – Eighty-eight thousand people were evacuated from their homes in Fort McMurray, Alberta, Canada as a wildfire ripped through the community, destroying approximately 2,400 homes and buildings.\n\nBULLET::::- 490 – K'an Joy Chitam I, ruler of Palenque (d. 565)\nBULLET::::- 612 – Constantine III, Byzantine emperor (d. 641)\nBULLET::::- 1238 – Emilia Bicchieri, Italian saint (d. 1314)\nBULLET::::- 1276 – Louis, Count of Évreux, son of King Philip III of France (d. 1319)\nBULLET::::- 1415 – Cecily Neville, Duchess of York (d. 1495)\nBULLET::::- 1428 – Pedro González de Mendoza, Spanish cardinal (d. 1495)\nBULLET::::- 1446 – Margaret of York (d. 1503)\nBULLET::::- 1461 – Raffaele Riario, Italian cardinal (d. 1521)\nBULLET::::- 1469 – Niccolò Machiavelli, Italian historian and philosopher (d. 1527)\nBULLET::::- 1479 – Henry V, Duke of Mecklenburg (d. 1552)\nBULLET::::- 1481 – Juana de la Cruz Vázquez Gutiérrez, Spanish abbess of the Franciscan Third Order Regular (d. 1534)\nBULLET::::- 1536 – Stephan Praetorius, German theologian (d. 1603)\nBULLET::::- 1632 – Catherine of St. Augustine, French-Canadian nurse and saint, founded the Hôtel-Dieu de Québec (d. 1668)\nBULLET::::- 1662 – Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann, German architect, designed the Pillnitz Castle (d. 1736)\nBULLET::::- 1678 – Amaro Pargo, Spanish corsair (d. 1747)\nBULLET::::- 1695 – Henri Pitot, French physicist and engineer, invented the Pitot tube (d. 1771)\nBULLET::::- 1729 – Florian Leopold Gassmann, Czech composer (d. 1774)\nBULLET::::- 1761 – August von Kotzebue, German playwright and author (d. 1819)\nBULLET::::- 1764 – Princess Élisabeth of France (d. 1794)\nBULLET::::- 1768 – Charles Tennant, Scottish chemist and businessman (d. 1838)\nBULLET::::- 1783 – José de la Riva Agüero, Peruvian soldier and politician, 1st President of Peru and 2nd President of North Peru (d. 1858)\nBULLET::::- 1814 – Adams George Archibald, Canadian lawyer and politician, 4th Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia (d. 1892)\nBULLET::::- 1826 – Charles XV of Sweden (d. 1872)\nBULLET::::- 1844 – Richard D'Oyly Carte, English talent agent and composer (d. 1901)\nBULLET::::- 1849 – Jacob Riis, Danish-American journalist and photographer (d. 1914)\nBULLET::::- 1849 – Bernhard von Bülow, German soldier and politician, Chancellor of Germany (d. 1929)\nBULLET::::- 1854 – George Gore, American baseball player and manager (d. 1933)\nBULLET::::- 1859 – August Herrmann, American executive in Major League Baseball (d.1931)\nBULLET::::- 1860 – Vito Volterra, Italian mathematician and physicist (d. 1940)\nBULLET::::- 1867 – Andy Bowen, Americ